). The genus 

Glaucium
Mill. (Papaveraceae)

belongs to the latest subfamily and comprises two sections (sect. 
Acropetala
Mory and sect. 

Glaucium

) with 28 species (78 synonyms), 3 subspecies, and 3 varieties of the herbaceous annual, biennial, and perennial plants worldwide mostly distributed in Europe, Central and Southwest Asia (The plant list, 2013: http://www.theplantl ist.org/tpl1.1/search?q= 
Glaucium
; http://www.plantsoftheworldonl ine.org/?q=glauciu). The plants belonging to the genus 

Glaucium
,

like other plants of the 
Papaveraceae
family, contain different classes of alkaloids. However, the plants are well known for their aporphinoids including, isoquinoline alkaloids which are pharmacologically active (

). For instance, glaucine as a major aporphine alkaloid isolated from the species of the genus (

), acts as a PDE4 inhibitor and calcium channel blocker. Besides, it has neuroleptic, bronchodilator, antitussive, and anti-inflammatory effects (

).

In different parts of the world, the plants have been used traditionally for the treatment of a diverse range of ailments such as treating pulmonary diseases and as laxative, sedative, anti-diabetic, and antidermatitis agents (

). The aerial parts of these plants have been prescribed as narcotics and hypnotics mainly in the form of infusions or decoctions and the seeds of the plants have been used as a laxative (Ibn Sin¯a, 1408; Ibn Beyṭ¯ar, 1422). Pharmacological studies have reported anti-acetylcholinesterase (anti-AChE) (

; 

), anti-proliferative, cytotoxic, anticancer (

), anti-nociceptive (

), antibacterial (

), and anti-inflammatory (

) activities of the plants belonging to 

Glaucium
species. 
G

. flavum
, known as yellow horn poppy, is one of the most studied species of this genus. The plant, native to Northern Africa, Western Asia, and Europe, exhibits various medicinal properties such as antioxidant, antitussive, bronchodilator, and hypoglycemic activities (

). According to a literature survey, many species of the genus are neither phytochemically, nor pharmacologically studied. The purpose of the present paper is to have a comprehensive review of the phytochemical and pharmacological aspects of the genus 

Glaucium

in order to have better insight for future studies and to benefit from their therapeutic potential.

