6.1.1.2. Anti-cancer activity. Glaucine has also been reported to have cytotoxic, antiviral, and antioxidant activities. For instance, in an in vitro study on human breast cancer cells, glaucine could inhibit the invasion of cancerous cells via blocking MMP-9 expression and activity dose-dependently (
). In another study, it was found that glaucine could inhibit MMP-9 expression by suppressing activation of the nuclear transcription factor NF-κB. Moreover, in two models of breast cancers, glaucine has been reported to have the ability to reverse the multi-drug resistance by inhibiting P-gp and BCRP. In addition, glaucine has exhibited synergistic effects with other cytotoxic drugs. For instance, glaucine (10 μM) could enhance the cytotoxicity of doxorubicin in Caco-2 and CEM ADR5000 cells 2.5–5.4 fold. In another study, glaucine could increase the cytotoxicity of mitoxantrone in MDA-MB-231 cancer cells, as a BCRP overexpressing breast cancer cell line, 2.5 fold and that of camptothecin 2.9-fold at 1 μM and 5 μM, respectively. It is worthy to mention that glaucine acts as a spasmolytic, adrenolytic, and antihydropic. Besides, its use is not associated with any dependency even after prolonged use. A feeling of sleepiness and tiredness, nausea, decreased blood pressure, and vomiting are the main side effects of glaucine. Moreover, glaucomatous visual hallucinations which are typical for hallucinogens have also been reported after glaucine consumption (
).

6.1.2.1. Anti-cancer activity. In a study, dicentrine could potentiate apoptosis in a549 lung adenocarcinoma cells and suppressed the invasion of these cancerous cells via modulation of NF-κB and activation of activator protein-1 (AP-1) (
). In addition, it could increase caspase-8, -9, -3, and poly (ADP-ribose) polymerase activities, downregulate the invasive proteins, and significantly block TAK1, p38, JNK, and Akt, leading to a decrease in the transcriptional activity of NF-κB and AP-1 (
). In another study, dicentrine showed anti-proliferative activities on A 549, a human lung cancer cell line, by inducing apoptosis, increasing the number of cells in the S phase significantly ( P < 0.05), and activating caspase-3 (
). In addition, studies show that dicentrine could significantly decrease telomerase activity by stabilizing G-quadruplex structure ( P < 0.05) (
).

Different analogs of dicentrine have been synthesized to improve its cytotoxic and anti-tumor activities (

). An analog of dicentrine could induce G2/M arrest and apoptosis by inhibiting topoisomerase II activity 
in vitro
(

). This analog, synthesized by base hydrolysis and N-alkylation, exhibited more potent cytotoxic activities than D-dicentrine in hepatoma, leukemia, colon adenocarcinoma, and epidermoid cancerous cells (

). In another 
in vitro
model of study on HL-60 leukemia cells, D-dicentrine and one of its analogs with an N-ethyl substitute and a cleavage of the N-bearing ring could induce apoptosis and G2/M arrest in the cells (

). The analog was 4.5-fold more potent in inducing apoptosis than D-dicentrine. Moreover, the analog showed 28-fold more inhibitory activity on topoisomerase II than D-dicentrine (

).

6.1.2.2. Anti-inflammatory activity. Regarding its anti-inflammatory activity, dicentrine could suppress inflammatory response through inhibiting NF-κB and AP-1 activation via blocking Akt and MAPKs signaling pathways in vitro (
). The pre-treatment of macrophages with dicentrine suppressed pro-inflammatory cytokines and mediators including TNF-α, IL-6, prostaglandin E2, and NO . It showed inhibitory activity on the expression of inducible NO synthase and cyclooxygenase-2. It could inhibit the NF-κB activation by suppressing the phosphorylation of NF-κB at Ser536, reduce the phosphorylation and nucleus translocation of AP-1, and suppress the myeloid differentiation factor 88, Akt and MAPKs signaling pathway, which are the upstream signaling regulators of AP-1 and NF-κB (
).

6.1.2.3. Anti-nociceptive activity. Anti-nociceptive effects have also been reported from dicentrine. For instance, oral administration of S- (+)-dicentrine ( 100 mg /kg) to mice could induce anti-nociceptive effects in acute and chronic inflammatory pain models (
). The anti-nociceptive activity of dicentrine has also been investigated by another research group (
). Administration of dicentrine ( 30–300 mg /kg) orally in mice could inhibit pain without causing changes in the motor performance dose-dependently (
).

6.1.2.4. Anticholinesterase activity.
Dicentrine and its derivatives such as dehydrodicentrine have exhibited anti-AChE in few studies (

). Studies show that dehydrodicentrine might be more potent than dicentrine. As an example, in a study using Ellman’ s AChE inhibition assay, dicentrine inhibited AChE activity with an IC 
50
value of 93.5 μg/mL (

) while in another study, dehydrodicentrine showed strong AChE inhibitory effects with the IC 
50
value of 2.98 μM (

).

6.1.2.5. Antiparasitic activity. Dicentrinone, another dicentrine derivative, showed a very potent leishmanicidal effect with IC 50 0.01 μM against promastigote forms of
Leishmania braziliensis
(
;
). This alkaloid also exhibited anti-parasitic activity against trypomastigote forms of
Trypanosoma cruzi
with IC 50 16.4 ± 1.7 μM, comparable to benznidazole (IC 50 18.7 ± 4.1 μM) as the positive control (
).

Cytotoxic and anti-nociceptive activities have been reported for corytuberine, another bioactive constituent from
Glaucium species.
Corytuberine showed a cytotoxic effect against SMMC-7721 cell line (IC 50 values of 73.22 ± 2.35 M) (
). In an animal model of study, administration of 6.3 and 12.5 mg /kg of (+)-corytuberine (i.p.) showed very potent anti-nociceptive effects in the writhing, hot plate, and the formalin tests (
).

6.2.1.2. Anti-cancer activity.
Studies show that chelerythrine is an antineoplastic agent showing cytotoxic effects on various malignant cells. Chelerythrine chloride downregulated β- catenin implicating the downregulation of cancer stem cells transcription factors such as MYC and SOX2. Besides, it could inhibit soft agar colony-forming, invasion, migration, and spheroid forming abilities of stem cell properties in non-small cell lung carcinoma (

). Studies also showed that chelerythrine could induce apoptosis through ROS-mediated ER stress and STAT3 pathways 
in vitro
(

). Similarly, the results from another 
in vitro
study showed that it could increase intracellular ROS leading to ER stress and cell apoptosis (

).

6.2.1.3. Anti-AChE activity.
Anti-AChE and butyrylcholinesterase (BChE) activities are other categories of biological effects reported for chelerythrine and its derivatives. In fact, chelerythrine is a well-known anti-AChE and anti-BChE (

; 

; 

). For example, chelerythrine and seven of its analogs, designed by structure imitation have shown strong anti-AChE activity (IC 
50
≤ 0.72 μM) compared to galantamine as the standard drug (

). Chelerythrine has also been reported to act on AChE and BChE through inhibiting both Aβ aggregation and disaggregating preformed Aβ aggregates (

).

6.2.2.1. Anticancer activity.
In an 
in vitro
study, sanguinarine could significantly inhibit cell proliferation and cell growth of thyroid cancer cells in a dose- and time-dependent manner (

). It exerted its effect via attenuating the expression of 
p
-STAT3 and through activation of apoptosis and autophagy (

). As an example, sanguinarine could induce apoptosis by inhibiting the JAK2/STAT3 signaling pathway in multiple myeloma cell lines and decrease cell viability through mitochondrial membrane potential loss, activation of caspase 3, 9, and cleavage of PARP. Sanguinarine treatment led to the downregulation of the anti-apoptotic proteins cyclin D, Bcl-2, Bclxl, and XIAP and upregulation of pro-apoptotic protein, Bax and mediated cellular DNA damage in the cells by ROS generation and glutathione depletion. In addition, the sub-toxic concentration of sanguinarine showed synergistic cytotoxic effects with anticancer drug bortezomib through decreasing the cell viability by induction of caspase-mediated apoptosis (

). The synergistic effects of sanguinarine with other anti-cancer drugs have also been reported. Sanguinarine could sensitize papillary thyroid cancer cells to the chemotherapeutic drug cisplatin (

). Similarly, in another 
in vitro
study on cisplatin-resistant ovarian cancer cells, sanguinarine could enhance cisplatin sensitivity via glutathione depletion (

). Interestingly, similar results were observed when using an integrated bioinformatics approach leading to the identification of 7 potential natural inhibitors, in which sanguinarine found the highest score. The results showed that sanguinarine, alone and in combination with cisplatin, could significantly decrease the proliferation of wt/resistant ovarian cancer cells and the growth of parental and resistant ovarian xenograft tumors (

). Taken together, inhibiting the nuclear colocalization, interaction with p-STAT3-Ser and 
p
-STAT3-Tyr (

), inducing apoptosis through targeting IGFBP-3 (

), inhibiting thioredoxin reductase (TrxR) (

), inhibiting epithelial–mesenchymal transition via targeting HIF-1α/TGF-β (

), regulating the TOX/DNA-PKcs/KU70/80 pathway (

), regulating the MAPK/JNK signaling pathway (

), increasing p53 and decreasing the expression of Bcl-2 and cyclin D1 (

) are some of the proposed mechanisms for anti-cancer activities of sanguinarine.

Studies show that dihydrosanguinarine has also potential anti-cancer activities through induction of apoptosis including mitochondrial membrane potential loss, increasing caspase-3 and -9 activities, cell cycle arrest at sub-G1, and loss of plasma membrane asymmetry (
). In a study, dihydrosanguinarine could regulate mut-p53/WT-p53 and the Ras/Raf/Mek/Erk pathway leading to the suppression of pancreatic cancer cells. Dihydrosanguinarine inhibited cell proliferation, migration, and invasion through cell cycle arrest and apoptosis (
). However,
found that sanguinarine might be more potent than dihydrosanguinarine (
). In this in vitro model of study, sanguinarine with IC 50 0.9 μM (after 4h) showed more potency than dihydrosanguinarine with IC 50 20 μM (after 24 h).

6.2.2.2. Glucose uptake.
Enhancing the glucose uptake is another activity reported for dihydrosanguinarine (

). In mouse 3 
T
3-L1 cells, dihydrosanguinarine could induce preadipocyte differentiation and lipid droplet accumulation through suppressing AMP-α, upregulating PPARγ expression and its target genes including Glut-4 and adiponectin, and reducing PPARγ phosphorylation (

).

6.2.2.3. Anti-AChE activity.
In a computational screening of some dietary phytochemicals in order to find potential anti-Alzheimer drugs, sanguinarine with some other natural compounds exhibited the most promising activities (

).

Chelidonine has not only been reported from the genus
Glaucium
, but also isolated from other plant species. It is a major alkaloid from
Chelidonium majus
, another member of the Papaveraceae family. There are a large number of papers reporting on the anti-inflammatory (
;
), anti-proliferative and anti-cancer activities of chelidonine. Table 3 summarizes some of the studies reporting the anti-tumor and anti-proliferative activities of this compound. In most of the studied cancerous cell lines, chelidonine could induce cell growth arrest mostly through apoptosis. Regarding the anti-inflammatory activities, chelidonine is reported to exhibit its beneficial effects through various mechanisms such as decreasing inflammatory mediators via inhibiting the TLR4/NF-κB signaling pathway, the NF-κB inflammatory pathways, and the expression of IL-4 and eotaxin-2 (O.
