Protopines are metabolically derived from the benzylisoquinoline alkaloid (
S
)-reticuline. Protopine is the prototype for this category of alkaloids and the most widely distributed one. That is why these 
types
of alkaloids are known as protopines (

). Protopine is a histamine 
H
1 antagonist, an analgesic agent with opioid effects, and a platelet aggregation inhibitor. Besides, numerous biological effects including cardiovasoprotective, anti-inflammatory, anti-thrombotic, anti-inflammatory, neuroprotective, anti-spasmodic, anti-viral, anti-bacterial, anti-fungal, and anti-parasitic activities have been reported from different compounds of this alkaloid category (

). Fagarine, muramine, protopine, and dihydroprotopine are the reported protopine alkaloids from the genus 

Glaucium

(
Table 4
).

Scoulerine has shown several biological properties including potent anti-proliferative, antimitotic, pro-apoptotic, anti-AChE (

), and antipsychotic (

) activities. However, the most promising effect reported is its anti-cancer activity (

). Increasing caspase-3/7 activity, bax and cytosolic Cyt 
C
expression, decreasing the expression of Bcl-2 and mitochondrial Cyt 
C
, upregulating p53 expression, inducing oxidative damage in cancerous cells via ROS generation, reducing GSH content and SOD activity are the observed mechanisms for this compound (

). In addition, it can reduce the activity of the mitochondrial dehydrogenases, induce the microtubule network breakdown, and increase the phosphorylation of Chk1 Ser345, Chk2 Thr68, and mitotic 
H
3 Ser10 (

), emphasizing the effects of scoulerine on microtubule structure and apoptosis (

).

